ce:section.ce:para:
As discussed in section 2.1, coil-only EMAT designs require large dynamic currents for efficient ultrasound generation, and hence a bespoke excitation circuit. The driving electronics for the experimental tests of the EMAT generation array consist of a capacitor bank discharged through a solid state switching device for each channel (see Fig. 2
                        ). The phase delays are applied by a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) unit and have a temporal resolution of 2.5 ns. The temporal current profile of the excitation pulse was measured by placing a small resistance of 0.1 

                              Ω

                         in series with the EMAT coil being driven. A voltage measurement across this resistance was used to determine the current passing through it, and hence the EMAT coil, through the use of Ohm's law. For a supplied pulse with a rise time of 1 μs, the peak current amplitude is 1.75 kA per channel (see Fig. 3
                        ).

Phase delays were applied in accordance with equation (3) to the four-element generation array to focus an incident pulse of longitudinal waves on the opposing face of a 22.5 cm thick as-cast steel slab sample. A single edge-field detection EMAT (constructed as described in section 3.3) was placed directly opposite; this was connected to an amplifier, which was then connected to an oscilloscope to measure the time-dependent voltage across the detection coil (see Fig. 12
                        ). An A-scan recording of the voltage history resulting from phased array generation was compared to the signal recorded when just a single generation element, placed directly opposite the detection coil, was fired (see Fig. 13
                        ). These measurements were taken with no coherent averaging, but were digitally filtered using a Butterworth bandpass filter with low and high pass bands of 0.1 and 5.0 MHz respectively, and an order parameter of 1.
